#--: Introduction

This document is the architectural map of the zerolang typechecker.
It is intended to be read #_*"before" opening
#~"src/ztypecheck.z" -- after reading it,
a contributor should know which structures the typechecker
maintains, how its code is partitioned, and where a particular
feature lives.

The companion document #~"compiler.pdoc" covers #_*"semantics" --
what ownership means, how the multi-granularity lock-conflict rule
works, what demand-driven resolution guarantees. This document
covers #_*"structure": data layout, dispatch, code organisation.
The two documents are deliberately split so that semantic rules
have a single source of truth (compiler.pdoc / ownership.pdoc) and
this one stays a navigation aid that does not rot when rule wording
changes.

#b:"Audience." A new contributor who has already read
#~"spec.pdoc", #~"ownership.pdoc", and the Semantic-Analyser
section of #~"compiler.pdoc".


#--: Pipeline Position

The typechecker sits between the parser and the C emitter:

#code language=text: """
  zast.ProgramData  (frozen post-parse)
      ↓   typecheck(program)
  ztyping.ZTyping  (mutable, holds all typecheck output)
      ↓
  zemitterc / zsqldump
"""

The parser hands the typechecker a #~"zast.ProgramData" -- an immutable
tree of #~"Node" values, each with a monotonic #~"nodeid". The
typechecker does not mutate AST nodes; instead it writes its results
into a single mutable container, #~"ztyping.ZTyping", keyed by
#~"nodeid". After #~"typecheck()" returns, the emitter and SQL dumper
read from both the #~"ProgramData" (shape) and the #~"ZTyping" (types,
ownership, locks, monomorphisations) without further analysis.

#b:"Demand-driven, single pass." Resolution starts at #~"main" and
descends only into names that are actually referenced. Names that
are never reached are never typechecked. The same property gives
cycle detection for free -- a name that is encountered while it is
already on the resolution stack is reported as a circular
dependency. See #~"compiler.pdoc:Demand-Driven Resolution" for the
rationale.


#--: Core Data Structures

The typechecker is built around five core record types and one
mutable container. Reading this section first makes
#~"ztypecheck.z" considerably easier to follow, because nearly
every function in it produces, mutates, or consults one of these.


#---: ZType -- the unified type descriptor

#~"ZType" (in #~"src/ztypes.z") is the #_*"only" type
representation in the compiler. There is no separate "kind",
"shape", or "schema" object: every type -- record, class, variant,
union, protocol, facet, function, unit, numeric, native -- is a
#~"ZType" with a #~"typetype" discriminator (the #~"ztypetype"
enum) and a set of optional fields.

Key fields:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"name": the simple name (e.g. #~"Point")]
  [#*: #~"typetype": the #~"ztypetype" enum
    (#~"RECORD", #~"CLASS", #~"VARIANT", #~"UNION", #~"PROTOCOL",
    #~"FACET", #~"FUNCTION", #~"UNIT", numerics, ...)]
  [#*: #~"enclosingTypeId": the enclosing unit type, or none
    for top-level units]
  [#*: #~"childrenIdMap": per-name monotonic child id,
    minted lazily by #~"allocChild". The id is the
    authoritative key for children in #~"ZTyping.typeChild" rows
    and for narrowing entries that need a numeric subject]
  [#*: #~"returnTypeId", #~"returnOwnership", #~"thisParamName":
    populated for function types]
  [#*: generic-state fields: #~"genericParams",
    #~"genericDefaults", #~"genericOriginId",
    #~"numericGenericParams", #~"isTagGenericOrigin"]
  [#*: #~"constValue": a literal value carried on a
    #~"ZType" used as either an as-block constant or a numeric
    generic-arg carrier (the #~"8" in #~"array<i64, 8>")]
  [#*: layout / memory metadata: #~"destructorName",
    #~"isHeapAllocated", #~"needsFieldCleanup",
    #~"isNullablePtr", #~"isBox" (see
    #~"representation_of_types.pdoc")]
  [#*: #~"createDisabled", #~"metaCreateId":
    unified-call-dispatch metadata: bare-name calls route through
    #~"children[create]" unless disabled, with #~"metaCreateId"
    holding the raw allocator]
  [#*: #~"cname": the C identifier the emitter uses]
  [#*: #~"typeId": monotonic id for SQL dumps]

A #~"ZType" carries identity-data only. #_*"Per-edge" metadata --
parameter ownership annotations, field defaults, lock/private
modifiers -- lives on #~"ZTyping.typeChild" rows (the flat
children table), not on the parent #~"ZType".


#---: ZVariable -- per-binding ownership carrier

#~"ZVariable" (#~"src/ztypes.z") wraps a #~"ZType" with the
state that is per-variable rather than per-type. A #~"ZVariable"
is created only for #_*"named runtime bindings" -- function
parameters, locals introduced by assignment, #~"with"-bindings,
for-loop iterators, and synth temps -- and referenced from
#~"ZEntry.varId". Expression-level results live on #~"ZExprResult",
not here; type and function definitions leave #~"ZEntry.varId"
unset.

#ul:
  [#*: #~"variableId": monotonic id]
  [#*: #~"ztypeId": the variable's resolved type]
  [#*: #~"ownership": #~"OWNED" or #~"BORROWED" (the
    2-state model described in #~"compiler.pdoc:Ownership and
    Lifetime")]
  [#*: #~"isPrivateAccess": carried through #~".private"
    typedef projections]
  [#*: #~"borrowOrigin": escape-analysis sentinel naming
    the function-local source this variable borrows from; none
    for parameters]
  [#*: #~"synthOrigin": pass-name string for variables
    synthesised by a compiler pass (e.g. #~"\"anf\"" for hoisted
    call temps); none for user-source variables]

Keeping ownership off #~"ZType" lets the same type be bound in two
scopes with different ownership, which is the common case.


#---: ZEntry -- a scope binding

#~"ZEntry" (#~"src/ztypes.z") is the unit of scope state. Every
piece of information the scope chain needs to track about a name
lives on an #~"ZEntry":

#ul:
  [#*: #~"entryId": monotonic id]
  [#*: #~"name", #~"ztypeId", #~"isDefinition"]
  [#*: #~"varId": optional #~"ZVariable" id (absent for
    type/function definitions and lock-only overlays)]
  [#*: #~"hasLock", #~"lockType", #~"lockHolder",
    #~"lockPath": lock state -- the lock kind, its holder, and the
    addressable path tuple #~"(root, f1, f2, ...)"]
  [#*: #~"narrowedSubtype", #~"narrowedSubtypeId",
    #~"excludedSubtypes", #~"excludedSubtypeIds": type
    narrowing for union / variant subjects in match arms, with
    id parallels for the future hot path]
  [#*: #~"originalZtypeId": the un-narrowed type, so the
    emitter can generate the C-level unwrap]
  [#*: #~"isTaken", #~"takenAt": consumed-binding state]

An entry is either a #_*"definition" (it introduces a name) or a
#_*"shadow / overlay" (it adjusts state for a name defined in an
outer scope). Definitions live in #~"BLOCK" scopes; shadows live
in #~"OVERLAY" or #~"CALL" scopes and disappear automatically when
their scope is popped. See #~"compiler.pdoc:Scope Environment" for
the three scope kinds.


#---: ZExprResult -- the result of checking an expression

Most expression-level helpers return #~"ZExprResult"
(#~"src/ztypes.z"), not a bare #~"ZType":

#ul:
  [#*: #~"ztypeId": the inferred type]
  [#*: #~"borrowTarget": the addressable path tuple
    #~"(root, f1, ...)" that this expression borrows from; the
    enclosing #~"checkAssignment" / call-argument check
    consumes it to install a borrow-scoped lock at the binding
    site]
  [#*: #~"privateAccess": propagated through
    #~".private" projections]

The #~"borrowTarget" mechanism keeps borrow-lock installation
out of deep expression code: the leaf method that knows the source
path stamps it onto the #~"ZExprResult", and the eventual binding
site installs the lock. The flow is described under
#~"ownership.pdoc:Borrow propagation".


#---: ZTyping -- the typecheck-output container

#~"ZTyping" (#~"src/ztyping.z") is the single mutable container
holding everything the typechecker computes. It is intentionally
ECS-shaped: instead of decorating parsed AST nodes with extra
columns, the typechecker writes into a set of per-#~"nodeid"
component maps.

Aggregate state:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"errors", #~"isError": error accumulator]
  [#*: #~"monoTypes", #~"monoFunctions": monomorphised
    generic instantiations, each paired with its origin AST
    definition]
  [#*: #~"funcAliases", #~"clonedMethods", #~"resolved":
    monomorphisation deduplication caches]
  [#*: #~"unitTypesById": Unit-AST nodeid → resolved unit
    ZType]

Component tables (each keyed by parsed-node #~"nodeid"):

#ul:
  [#*: #~"nodeType", #~"nodeConst": per-Node type
    and compile-time constant]
  [#*: #~"callKind", #~"callCallableTypeId",
    #~"exprCallKind": call classification and control-kind
    routing]
  [#*: #~"doHasBreak", #~"caseSubjectTaken",
    #~"forIterBindings": per-construct flags]
  [#*: #~"ifTakenVars", #~"caseTakenVars": post-branch
    ownership-cleanup lists]
  [#*: #~"atomNarrowedSubtype", #~"atomOriginalZtype",
    #~"atomChildId": per-AtomId narrowing stamps]
  [#*: #~"dpParentTaggedType", #~"dpChildId": per-
    DottedPath parent-type and child-id stamps]
  [#*: #~"withOwnership", #~"withAliasOf",
    #~"assignAliasOf": per-binding alias/ownership stamps]
  [#*: #~"projectedArgs": per-NamedOperation protocol-projection
    stamps]
  [#*: #~"typeChild", #~"typeGenericArg": flat
    children / generic-args tables]

The SQL dumper writes one row per component entry, so every table
has a direct SQL representation.


#---: ZSymbolTable and ZScope

#~"ZSymbolTable" (#~"src/zenv.z") is the scope stack the
typechecker uses for #_*"all" variable state -- type, ownership,
lock state, narrowing, taken state. There is no separate flow-
typing structure: state changes are recorded as new entries in
overlay scopes; scope pop is the only thing that undoes them.

#ul:
  [#*: #~"ZScope": a #~"kind" (#~"BLOCK", #~"CALL", or
    #~"OVERLAY"), a #~"name", a monotonic #~"scopeId", and an
    #~"entryStart" index into the table's flat entry list.
    Entries are scanned linearly (typical scope has fewer than
    ten); unreachable scopes are tracked in a side set]
  [#*: #~"ZSymbolTable": a stack of #~"ZScope" frames over a flat
    #~"entries" list, plus #~"history" (popped scopes, retained
    for SQL dump) and #~"scopeLog" (append-only log of push/pop
    events with parent ids and sequence numbers)]

Three scope kinds (full description in
#~"compiler.pdoc:Scope Environment"):

#ul:
  [#*: #~"BLOCK" -- language constructs (function, do, for, if,
    with, match arm). Can contain definitions.]
  [#*: #~"CALL" -- pushed before processing call arguments, popped
    after the call. Locks installed here vanish when the call
    returns.]
  [#*: #~"OVERLAY" -- shadow records for a variable defined in an
    outer scope (new lock, narrowing, taken state).]

Lock state is keyed on a path tuple #~"(root, f1, ..., fn)" stored
on #~"ZEntry.lockPath". #~"ZEntry.name" always equals #~"path[0]" so the
linear scan stays cheap; the full tuple is consulted only by the
prefix-overlap rule. Key APIs (all on #~"ZSymbolTable"):

#ul:
  [#*: #~"lookup", #~"lookupVarId", #~"lookupVarNameById"
    -- name → type / variable resolution]
  [#*: #~"tryLock" -- attempt to install a lock; returns the
    installed lock or a conflict description. Multi-granularity
    rule is in #~"lockAcquireConflict"]
  [#*: #~"findExclusiveLock", #~"isPathLocked" -- access-
    site enforcement (used by lock-escape checks)]
  [#*: #~"narrow", #~"exclude" -- install a narrowing or
    exclusion overlay entry on the current scope]

The lock conflict logic lives in #~"zenv.z", not in
#~"ztypecheck.z". The typechecker only chooses #_*"when" to
install a lock; the rule for whether it conflicts is owned by
the scope module.


#--: Code Map of #~"ztypecheck.z"

The file is long, but it organises top-to-bottom roughly as
follows. Functions are listed by name (no line numbers -- they
rot fast; #~"grep -n" finds them quickly). Use this map to scroll
into the right region; read prose below for the semantics.

#table:
  [#tr: [#th: Band] [#th: Key functions]]
  [#tr: [#td: Pass setup]
        [#td: module-level #~"typecheck" entry -- resolving
              stack, unit cache, call-id stack, and the
              fresh-temp counter (#~"ZTyping.nextTempId")]]
  [#tr: [#td: Entry point]
        [#td: #~"typecheck" -- starts at #~"main", drives demand-
              driven resolution and body checking, returns the
              accumulated error list]]
  [#tr: [#td: Unit-level name resolution]
        [#td: #~"resolveDef" (dispatches over #~"nodetype"),
              #~"resolveUnitBody"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Type-definition resolvers]
        [#td: #~"resolveFunction",
              #~"resolveRecord", #~"resolveClass",
              #~"resolveUnion",
              #~"resolveVariant",
              #~"resolveProtocol",
              #~"resolveFacet",
              #~"resolveInlineGenericUnit",
              #~"resolveData"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Name and typeref resolution]
        [#td: #~"resolveTyperefShell", #~"lookupTyperef",
              #~"checkDotted", #~"dottedParentName", and the
              #~"type" / #~"this" keyword resolvers]]
  [#tr: [#td: Monomorphisation]
        [#td: #~"mintMono", #~"genericTypeKey",
              #~"resolveMonos", #~"cloneUnitMethod",
              #~"validateGenericTypeArgs"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Function body]
        [#td: #~"checkFunctionBody", #~"checkMethodBodies",
              #~"checkBodies"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Statements]
        [#td: #~"checkStatement",
              #~"checkStmtInner",
              #~"checkStatementLine",
              #~"checkAssignment",
              #~"checkReassignment", #~"checkSwap"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Expressions]
        [#td: #~"checkExpression", #~"checkValue",
              #~"checkAtomid",
              #~"checkString"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Dotted paths]
        [#td: #~"checkDotted" -- auto-call coercion gate;
              handles #~".take" / #~".release" / #~".borrow" /
              #~".lock" / #~".private"]]
  [#tr: [#td: Calls]
        [#td: #~"checkCall",
              #~"checkMissingCallArgs",
              #~"lockCallArg", #~"installBorrowLocks",
              #~"checkProjectionCreate",
              #~"checkTypedefCreate",
              #~"checkTypedefBorrow", and the argument-take /
              lock-escape helpers]]
  [#tr: [#td: Special call forms]
        [#td: #~"checkBinop" and the return-call
              (#~"children[create]" construction) and
              string-convert dispatch]]
  [#tr: [#td: Control flow]
        [#td: #~"checkIf",
              #~"checkFor", #~"checkWith",
              #~"checkCase" / #~"checkClause" (match arm checking,
              including branch narrowing and post-match
              exclusion), #~"checkBoxConstruction"]]


#--: Dispatch Mechanism

Per the project convention (#~"CLAUDE.md"), the typechecker
dispatches on the #~"nodetype" discriminator rather than runtime
type tests. The pattern appears in two forms:

#ul:
  [#*: #b:"Closed dispatch keyed by #~"nodetype"" -- e.g. the
    definition resolvers. Used where the set of cases is closed
    and known up front (type-definition resolvers, statement-line
    kinds).]
  [#*: #b:"Inline match on" #~"node.nodetype" -- used inside
    #~"checkExpression", #~"checkValue", and a few similar
    high-fan-out helpers where a flat match reads more clearly
    than a table.]

After the discriminator check, #~"cast()" narrows the node to the
concrete #~"Node" arm; see #~"src/zast.z".


#--: Resolution Stack and Cycle Detection

Resolution is keyed by #_*"definition nodeid", not by synthesized
dotted-string names. Every definition is one AST node with one stable
#~"nodeid", and that node is shared across every reference to it, so
the same definition always resolves to the same cached type no matter
which unit asks. A resolved cache maps #~"defn.nodeid -> ZType";
a list-shaped resolution stack records the definitions currently
being resolved (each frame carrying its unit name, def-id, ztype,
and AST node). The flow is:

#ol:
  [#*: Unit-name resolution looks the definition up in the unit's
    member table, then checks the resolved cache keyed by
    #~"defn.nodeid". Hit: return immediately.]
  [#*: Cache miss: push a resolution frame for #~"defn.nodeid" onto
    the stack and dispatch to the appropriate #~"resolve*" resolver
    by #~"nodetype".]
  [#*: If a nested resolution re-enters the same definition, the
    resolver finds its #~"def_id" on the stack and reports a cycle
    error.]
  [#*: On success, the resolver pops the stack frame and writes
    the final #~"ZType" into the resolved cache under #~"defn.nodeid".]

The emitter and SQL dump read #~"ZTyping.resolved", a qualified-name
#~"({unit}.{member} -> ZType)" projection of the nodeid cache built
at the end of #~"typecheck".

The #~"type" keyword (in receiver position) resolves to the type
at the bottom of the resolving stack, so a method body can refer
to its own enclosing type without naming it. #~"this" works
similarly.


#--: Type-name resolution and the canonical-id rule

A bare type name (the #~"i64" in #~"x: i64", a conformance marker, a
field or parameter type) resolves #_*"current-unit-relative", mirroring
the module search path in #~"units.pdoc": the #_*"current unit" first,
then the stdlib units (#~"system", #~"collections", #~"io", #~"core",
#~"os", #~"cli"). First match wins, so a type defined in the current
unit #_*"shadows" a same-named stdlib builtin. Two functions implement
this:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"definingUnitFor(currentUnit, name)" -- the declare-before-bind
    index (built upfront by #~"indexUnitDefs"): which unit defines
    #~"name" for a reference in #~"currentUnit", current-unit first.
    #~"resolveAtomType" routes a name atom through it, get-or-declaring
    the ONE canonical id via #~"declareCanonicalType".]
  [#*: #~"lookupTyperef(mainName, base)" -- looks #~"base" up in the
    #~"resolved" cache over the same precedence. Despite its parameter
    name, #~"mainName" is the #_*"search-root unit": the #_*"current"
    unit at most call sites, the program's main unit at a few. It is
    not unconditionally main-rooted.]

Cross-unit references are #_*"dotted" (#~"zast.Node", #~"io.File"),
resolved by the named unit; bare names never reach across units except
to the stdlib fallback. (The same-named-directory #_*"submodule" feature
in #~"units.pdoc" -- a unit #~"foo.z" with a private #~"foo/" directory --
is implemented in the parser's #~"loadUnit"; the current corpus and the
self-hosted compiler use flat units + dotted references, so its bare-name
resolution is not exercised end-to-end at typecheck.)

#b:"The canonical-id rule." A definition resolves #_*"once", into one
canonical type id keyed by its #~"defn.nodeid" (with #~"defined_in_unit"
recording the owning unit). That id #_*"is" the type's identity -- not
its name. Downstream passes #_*"trust" the locked id and never re-resolve
a type by its name: the C emitter derives a type's C form from the id
(via #~"typeRefC" / #~"scalarCTypeFor" / #~"cTypeForNameTid"), never from
the name, so a user type that shadows a builtin scalar
(#~"i64: record { ... }") emits #_*"its" struct, while the system #~"i64"
reached through the same name keeps the C scalar. Re-resolving by name
would collapse the two onto whichever the search-root unit wins -- the
bug class the #~"make shadow-guard" ratchet prevents from returning.


#--: Cross-Cutting Concerns

Each subsection below points at #_*"where" a concern lives in the
typechecker. For #_*"why" it works that way, follow the links to
the semantic documents.


#---: Ownership enforcement

The 2-state ownership model (see #~"compiler.pdoc:Ownership and
Lifetime") is enforced at the assignment and call sites:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"checkAssignment" -- definition site. Records the
    new variable's ownership in a fresh #~"ZVariable", consumes
    any #~"ZExprResult.borrowTarget" by installing a borrow
    lock.]
  [#*: #~"checkReassignment" -- enforces that the LHS variable
    is currently #~"OWNED" and that the RHS provides the
    appropriate ownership; resets narrowing and re-runs lock
    escape checks.]
  [#*: #~"checkSwap" -- symmetric ownership preservation.]
  [#*: the argument-site #~".take" -- transfers ownership from
    the caller's binding into the callee's parameter.]

Parameters default to #~".borrow"; #~".take" and #~".lock" are
the opt-in transfers. The annotations live on the
#~"ZTyping.typeChild" rows (the param-ownership column), not on
the parameter #~"ZType".


#---: Lock checking

The typechecker chooses #_*"when" to install a lock; #~"zenv.z"
owns the conflict rule (#~"lockAcquireConflict") and the
prefix-overlap path test (#~"pathsOverlap"). Two scopes of
locks, both described in #~"compiler.pdoc:Lock Checking":

#ul:
  [#*: #b:"Call-scoped" -- installed by #~"lockCallArg" inside a
    #~"CALL" scope that wraps argument processing. The leaf is
    #~"EXCLUSIVE"; every intermediate prefix is #~"SHARED".]
  [#*: #b:"Borrow-scoped" -- installed by
    #~"installBorrowLocks" when a binding takes a borrow into
    a #~"BLOCK" scope (#~".borrow", #~".lock", #~".stringview",
    #~"with", or a #~".lock"-param transfer). Persists for the
    lifetime of the binding's scope; released by scope pop or
    explicit #~".release".]

The aggregate-lock-escape check runs at storage sites (field
writes) and at return sites; it consults #~"isPathLocked" on
the scope chain to reject a write/return that would let a locked
value escape its scope.

Self-overlap during a single call (e.g.
#~"f.method bv: f.byteview") is permitted via the call-identity
stack and #~"zlockholder" tagging: #~"tryLock"
skips the conflict check when the existing holder matches the
current call's identity.


#---: Borrow correctness for parameters

Deep methods that take a borrow into a return value record the
source path on a pending-borrow slot, which
#~"checkExpression" captures into #~"ZExprResult.borrowTarget"
and clears so it cannot leak across statements (see
#~"takePendingBorrow" / #~"drainPendingBorrow"). The binding site
(#~"checkAssignment" or the call-argument check) then
installs the borrow lock against the actual destination scope.
The dedicated #~".take" / #~".borrow" / #~".lock" / #~".release" /
#~".private" handling lives in #~"checkDotted".


#---: Monomorphisation

Generic types and functions are monomorphised by deep-cloning
the original AST subtree, binding the generic parameters to
concrete types, and re-running the standard resolvers on the
clone.

#ul:
  [#*: #~"mintMono" -- entry for generic type
    instantiation. Builds a deduplication key via
    #~"genericTypeKey" (over arg #~"(name, constValue)"
    pairs so numeric generics also dedupe), reuses an existing
    instantiation if present, otherwise clones and registers
    into #~"ZTyping.monoTypes".]
  [#*: #~"cloneUnitMethod" -- per-function variant.
    Clones the function AST, binds generic params, typechecks
    the clone with the mono context in scope.]
  [#*: #~"validateGenericTypeArgs" -- enforces generic
    constraints on a candidate argument type.]

Cloned nodes carry #~"synthOrigin" (the pass-name string) so the
SQL dump can attribute them to monomorphisation
rather than to the user. Node synthesis is described in
#~"compiler.pdoc:Synthesis Toolkit"; the same machinery is used by
per-call argument hoisting.

#~"is native" methods (the compiler-provided collection methods
on #~"array", #~"List", #~"Map", #~"str", etc.) are #_*"not"
special-cased -- they are cloned alongside user methods. The
only requirement is that their declaration in
#~"lib/system/system.z" or #~"lib/system/collections.z" carries
the #~"is native" form. Resolution flows through the standard
child-lookup path.


#---: Type narrowing

Narrowing for #~"union" and #~"variant" subjects in match arms
is implemented via overlay entries. When a match arm narrows
subject #~"s" to subtype #~"ok", an overlay #~"ZEntry" with
#~"narrowedSubtype: \"ok\"" is pushed onto the arm's scope.
Inside the arm, name lookup for #~"s" finds this entry first and
returns the narrowed type. The arm scope is popped at end of
arm; narrowing resets automatically.

Post-match #_*"exclusion" is the dual: arms that diverge
(return, break, panic) contribute their handled subtypes to an
#~"excludedSubtypes" entry placed on the parent scope after the
match. Subsequent code that re-accesses #~"s" as an excluded
subtype is rejected.

Assignment-based narrowing (e.g. #~"x: Result.ok 42") places a
narrowing entry in the current scope at definition time;
reassignment resets it.

Both narrowing and exclusion carry id parallels
(#~"narrowedSubtypeId", #~"excludedSubtypeIds") minted via
#~"ZType.allocChild". String fields remain authoritative; the
ids are the hot-path key prepared for future migration to the
SQL-backed representation.


#---: Auto-call coercion

A no-user-arg method dotted path read in value position
(#~"v: s.stringview", #~"p1.distance" inside a string
interpolation) is auto-called to its return type. The coercion
lives entirely in #~"checkDotted" and is gated by a
coerce-to-return flag. #~"checkCall" clears the
flag when resolving its own callable, so explicit calls
(#~"obj.method named: arg") see the function type and dispatch
normally instead of constructing the return type. Path
resolution itself is context-free: it
always returns the FUNCTION type for a method path. Behaviour is
identical for #~"is native" and user-defined methods.


#---: Unified call dispatch

A type used in callable position is rewritten through the
unified-dispatch route. The bare-name construction call
#~"Point x: 1 y: 2" resolves the callee to the #~"Point"
#~"ZType", then looks up #~"children[create]" on that type to
get the actual constructor. The mechanics live in the return-call
dispatch; #~"meta.create" on the
parent #~"ZType" carries the compiler-generated raw allocator
when one is needed. #~"create: null" in the type's #~"as" block
disables bare-name construction (the case for #~"union" and
#~"variant" where subtype selection is required).


#--: Error Reporting

Type errors are #~"zast.ErrorData" value objects, appended to
#~"ZTyping.errors" via the #~"addError" helper. Errors are never
raised as exceptions; the typechecker tries to continue
collecting errors past the first failure where the AST permits.
Error codes (the #~"err" variant in #~"src/zast.z") are grouped:

#ul:
  [#*: E0001-E0099 -- parser / syntax (raised earlier in the
    pipeline)]
  [#*: E0100-E0199 -- type resolution]
  [#*: E0200-E0299 -- ownership]
  [#*: E0300-E0399 -- call / argument]
  [#*: E0400-E0499 -- generic / monomorphisation]

The diagnostic location is taken from the offending AST node's
#~"loc" / #~"Token". After #~"typecheck()" returns, the caller
inspects #~"ZTyping.errors" to decide whether to proceed to
emission.


#--: What Lives Elsewhere

Module boundaries the typechecker relies on:

#ul:
  [#*: #~"src/ztypes.z" -- #~"ZType", #~"ZVariable",
    #~"ZEntry", #~"ZExprResult", #~"ZTypeRegistry",
    plus the #~"ztypetype" / #~"zownership" /
    #~"zparamownership" / #~"zlockstate" / #~"zscopekind" /
    #~"zsubtype" / #~"zcontrolkind" / #~"zbuiltinfunc" /
    #~"zlockholderkind" / #~"zlockholder" enums, and the shared
    manglers #~"mangleFuncName" / #~"mangleVarName"]
  [#*: #~"src/ztyping.z" -- the #~"ZTyping" container,
    #~"ZTypeChild" / #~"ZTypeGenericArg" flat-table rows]
  [#*: #~"src/zenv.z" -- #~"ZSymbolTable", #~"ZScope",
    #~"ZScopeLogRow", the lock-conflict logic
    (#~"lockAcquireConflict", #~"pathsOverlap"), narrowing
    / exclusion installers]

Collection-type predicates (#~"typeIsReftype", #~"typeIsValtype",
...), node synthesis, and the monomorphisation dedup hashing have
no separate module -- they live within #~"src/ztypecheck.z" itself.


#--: Reading Order

When opening the typechecker for the first time, read in this
order:

#ol:
  [#*: #~"src/ztypes.z" -- the type definitions in this
    file are the vocabulary for everything else.]
  [#*: #~"src/ztyping.z" -- the #~"ZTyping" container makes the
    component-table architecture concrete.]
  [#*: #~"src/zenv.z" -- the scope stack and the lock-conflict
    rule. The semantics of "what makes two locks conflict" lives
    here, not in the typechecker.]
  [#*: #~"src/ztypecheck.z" -- enter via the Code Map above.
    A good first dive is #~"typecheck" → #~"resolveDef" →
    #~"resolveFunction" → #~"checkFunctionBody" →
    #~"checkStatement" → #~"checkExpression" →
    #~"checkCall". That path touches almost every cross-
    cutting concern in turn.]


#--: Related Documents

#ul:
  [#*: #~"compiler.pdoc" -- the pipeline overview and the
    semantic descriptions of demand-driven resolution,
    monomorphisation, ownership, scope environment, lock
    checking, type narrowing, and the synthesis toolkit. This
    document is the structural companion to that one.]
  [#*: #~"ownership.pdoc" -- the full specification of
    ownership states, parameter annotations
    (#~".take" / #~".borrow" / #~".lock"), and per-call atomic
    processing.]
  [#*: #~"representation_of_types.pdoc" -- type layout
    (#~"destructor_name", #~"is_heap_allocated",
    #~"needs_field_cleanup", #~"is_box") and the stack-vs-heap
    strategy.]

#b:"Anti-duplication note." Semantic rules live in
#~"compiler.pdoc" and #~"ownership.pdoc"; type layout lives in
#~"representation_of_types.pdoc". This document is the map. If a
rule's wording needs to change, change it there, not here.
